.TH "URLPATTERN.PASSWORD" "3JS" "August 22, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
URLPattern.password \- URLPattern: password property
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This feature is available in Web Workers.
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]password\f[B]\f[R] read\-only property of the
\f[CR]URLPattern\f[R] interface is a string containing the pattern used
to match the password part of a URL.
.PP
This is the normalized value of the password pattern passed to the
constructor or the default value (\f[CR]\(dq*\(dq\f[R]), which matches
any password.
.SH VALUE
A string.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic usage
The following example creates a \f[CR]URLPattern\f[R] object with
\f[CR]correct\-horse\-battery{\-staple}?\f[R] for the
\f[CR]password\f[R] part and logs the property.
This pattern matches the passwords \f[CR]correct\-horse\-battery\f[R]
and \f[CR]correct\-horse\-battery\-staple\f[R].
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] pattern = \f[B]new\f[R] URLPattern({ password: \(dqcorrect\-horse\-battery{\-staple}?\(dq });
console.log(pattern.password); \f[I]// \(aqcorrect\-horse\-battery{\-staple}?\(aq\f[R]
console.log(pattern.test(\(dqhttps://user:correct\-horse\-battery\(atexample.com\(dq)); \f[I]// true\f[R]
.EE
